European inflation has slipped in food
The accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is due first of all to the rapid growth in the price of food.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, with an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent - after 2.6 per cent of October - announced the Luxembourg-based Union Statistical Office.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely - the Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the United States, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut off the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "we have to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
The inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, hit the 12-year record, while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation was triggered in the euro area as a result of the galloping food and energy prices.
The end-of-wheat contributions increased by 88 per cent and the soybean contribution also reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold almost 100 dollars a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 per cent today to 2.5 per cent, but by 2009 it will now fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will continue in the next 3 to 4 months about 3 per cent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during the year 2008.
Gallup anticipates a government crisis
After a long stalemate, in early December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its peak since 2002, while the Gallup never before experienced such a low level - 13% - for the Socialists.
The difference in the case of secure party electors - due to the greater firmness of opposition electors - would mean more than two-thirds (71 per cent) support compared to one-fifth support for socialists (20 per cent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach the limit necessary to have any parliamentary scans: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the secure voters there are one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 per cent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation particularly bad, while another 46 per cent believe that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As for the next year, the majority of the population had a deteriorating situation and only one tenth expected improvement.
In December, 71 per cent of the consulates, higher than any previous Gallup survey, estimated that the President of the Government was rather ill-functioning than well.
13% of the consulates rely on or rely heavily on Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38% of the consulates.
54 per cent of the population do not trust the head of government at all, and 27 per cent do not trust the president of the Youth Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced against the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While, after the October riots last year, 35 per cent considered that it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, this proportion is currently only 20 per cent, while the relative majority (33 per cent) believes that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
The interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 per cent of respondents to the question on participation responded that they would surely participate and another 20 per cent said that they are likely to participate.
In a comparative way, in "general elections to be held this Sunday" only 55 per cent of the population and 15 per cent believe their participation is likely to take place. Based on the current intentions of the electors, there is no doubt about the outcome of the popular consultation.
74 per cent of the population would disapprove of the payment of school fees, 79 per cent of the medical service and 84 per cent of the hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of the voters would reject the introduction of study rights, the payment for medical consultations and the payment of hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
They maintained the average price increase of 16 percent in the hypermarkets of the commercial gold triangle of Budaörs, with the difference that this year VAT has not been increased.
Napi Gazdaság's article
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the commercial gold triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the Napi daily, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth much higher than the thousand HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already been "fired" in December last year, this did not show a drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price far below the nine thousand HUF, today they cannot do it for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10 573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a strong increase in the turkey breast steak, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with two-litre redeemable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even at the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in the Napi Auchan basket was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased with 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent of the prices in the Napi basket.
Comparing the values of last year's most expensive basket with that of this year's cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year's cheapest and last year's most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during Christmas last year prices were felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, that supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the price change on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of the movement of a product, he may lose an important profit in the margin that is in line with the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such ends as a result of the increase in VAT, which the most expensive was higher than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, as the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Compared to the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets more than 30 percent of the price of basic consumer goods grew.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some basic foods, recorded in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 per cent.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of the egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, as in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst of cases just 10% increase in prices.
According to all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, which can impose the drastic increase in prices even to multinationals.
The hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trade triangle, they are constantly talking about positive results.
According to our experiences, most of the consumers in the three shops visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking preserved food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, the three shops formed large queues ahead of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country the sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the revenues are below their plans and not only for food, but also for household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, first of all due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The health circumstances in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favour the control of infections - says the doctor-head of department of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a contagion with MRSA has been diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of the antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly thereafter as a result of the MRSA infection and since then no major surgery has been performed for the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of 10 December this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multiresistant agents have been recorded in the Nosocomialis Surveillance National System - said Karolina Böröcz, a doctor-head of department of the National Epidemiology Centre.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been safely recorded, of the rest there is no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of humans carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
The infections produced by the SA (e.g., inflammation of the throat, amigdalitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is overused or misapplied to antibiotics, bacteria that usually react well to antibiotics are transformed into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and are quickly infected under inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound or septicemia infections, first of all to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to the elderly or to people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistance
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff care for them in rubber gloves and mask and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients hospitalized are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so infection can not be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the sick who carry the MRSA in their body.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when the MRSA infections already occur visible in the patient - said the doctor-head of department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict arrangements for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological patterns.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, that is, microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less common in the case of ambulant patients or in basic care - Karolina Böröcz said.
It's saved with the disinfectants.
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, the washing of hands, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also considerable deficiencies in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by drop transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - it has added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are carried out, fewer such infections are recorded or the infection of the pathogen may be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expenditure for the National Health Insurance Fund, and is therefore fought against it in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The program appears to be successful, according to data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative control of alcoholemia by the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report has been made on the case of the fatal accident caused by the police commander of the XXII district.
It can be excluded the possibility that led drunk or in a stunned state that since then resigned commander of the police of the district XXII, who on Tuesday hit and caused the death of a passer-by - said on Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the General Prosecutor's Office of the Capital, after having prepared the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary alcohol control that had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcoholic drink before putting himself behind the steering wheel.
The then head of the police station of the XXII district, on Tuesday with his private vehicle when he turned to Kossuth Lajos street of the XXII district, hit a 55-year-old man, who was trying to cross the street, but not in the designated pedestrian area.
(This last fact, that is, the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Transit Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way to bend.)
The passer-by lost his life after being hospitalized.
The district police leader resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very touched by the case.
The investigation of the case is carried out by the Budapest Office of the Prosecutor of Investigation.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the beginning worked with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
The Hungarian finance minister János Veres and the vice-president of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total value of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget transport and environmental protection projects, to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund grant, of which the parties had already signed a credit contract of EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit contract is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective for Hungary, and the decision will be taken later on when the credit contract is extended.
The parties signed a contract for EUR 50 million for innovations, which the budget will use mainly for the innovation and research project at the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary completed the details of the Metro financing with the EU, it will again address the issue that if necessary or not to change the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this can take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary in the amount of €8.4 billion.
The interest of the appropriations is in accordance with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the credit at the disposal of the debtor.
