Fodor and the six for hundreds of Hungarians
According to the Minister of the Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the expert level will be completed on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official opening will continue the negotiations at the ministerial level on the post-2012 international climate regime.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world discuss the Bali Road Map, which it has on the post-emission reduction period, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
At present, lively discussions are taking place between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures at the moment, although it tends to agree that, compared to the 1990 situation, the emissions of greenhouse gases will be reduced by 25 to 40 per cent by 2020.
Another major theme of the conference is that if industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are or are not willing to provide material and technological support to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the aid to be provided to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be headed by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit."
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for the Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent to 2020, as compared with the 1990 level, regardless of whether the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed or not, and is prepared to commit itself to reducing even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capacities.
Gábor Fodor noted that the countries that signed the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to a decline of 5.2 per cent, within which the then 15 EU Member States committed themselves to an 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce the emissions of greenhouse gases by 6 per cent over the period 1985-87, which our country will fulfil - the press release of the Ministry of the Environment points out.
Much is at stake in Balí, since in two years' time the international long-term climate policy agreement will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments, made in the Kyoto Protocol, would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN international scientific association dealing with climate change, which was won by the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would lead to a delay in reducing emissions and would not prevent an increase of more than 2o C in the Earth's average temperature, a fact that scientists believe would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video dealer publish recordings of recorded actions in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First, the British air force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: the special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini-cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operating body, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers who have been thus charged to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in spring 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
The air force had originally loaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs almost nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - the BBC has told the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - but inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'être of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the recelously edited and censored recordings, the distributor also has amateur videos, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak as much as possible of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, many videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different way to recruit with free-downloadable video games, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers.
