A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the destinies of 17.5 million victims of the Hitlerian regime, are in free access.
The 47 million file documents, stored on 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far available only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is to say, individually and nominatively, at the request of an old victim or his right-holders.
The eleven States responsible for its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to search engines and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow search "particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominating documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or the mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or of the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after war in a practical purpose: to find the peasants deported or subjected to compulsory work and, possibly, to provide them with proof of their detention, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Anti-Semitism Search Centre at Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
