In parallel to its parliamentary procedure, which ended today with the Congress's vote on the amendments to the draft in the Senate, the Government has submitted to the public the regulations that will develop the new law, with the aim of bringing both of them into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members and senators to negotiate and agree on the best rules in order to ensure the protection of investors and to regulate in detail the activities of the institutions in order to make the markets function efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves the modernization of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new legislation will provide financial advisory services to both specialized and natural or legal firms and create a new type of financial service firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the implementation of operations on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are added to multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment firms to disseminate information on the key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management on the market and requires them to keep a record of all the operations they carry out, in order to facilitate the monitoring by the CNMV.
In its move to the Congress's Economic Committee, several changes were made, including that the securitised debts are considered a "complex" financial instrument given its high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated by the debt of US high-risk mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally define the functions that can be carried out by graduates in Economics and Business 30 years after the adoption in 1977 of the royal decree which delimits the professional functions reserved for economists.
The Senate, for its part, incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as that of the mediator, who will work for his own benefit, will not require the authorisation of the CNMV and will be able to provide its services for the marketing of products and for the collection of customers to different investment companies at the same time.
