New fears about gas between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute over the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk that it will affect Russia's export of fuel to Western Europe.
The majority of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine, so each round between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit rates.
A previous dispute last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The last dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, the monopolic owner of the gas, Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money that Ukraine had to pay for the Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom stated that it will charge more to Ukraine, as it has committed itself to pay an extra 50 per cent in 2008 for the gas coming from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it might be that Ukraine pays 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transits for gas during the talks," Ukrainian Minister of Economy Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"Changes in gas prices should not be related to our arguments about the levels of transit rates [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut supply to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a fall in exports to Western Europe, which quickly increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of the EU's supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supply with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations in Central Asia.
NHS "must test foreign workers"
The Scottish NHS needs to control the criminal record records of employees from outside Europe, a vigilante said.
The recommendation of Auditor General Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was found to be related to the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea how many foreign staff it has.
However, his report noted other controls that are carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor-general checked the number of foreign staff recruited outside the European economic area, following the attacks at Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep was hit at the doors of the airport's terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who acted at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, accused of alleged car bomb attacks in the United Kingdom.
NHS hopes to carry out pre-employment checks on candidates, to ensure that they comply with the qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the Scottish health board uses "Disclosure Scotland" to carry out criminal record checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of Britain.
The Auditor General's report recommends, among other measures, that the boards should have the guidance of the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside of Britain.
"Although we find some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review," the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: "our report highlights the areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available in the number of NHS foreign staff."
BMA Scottish President Dr. Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is," he explained.
Scottish health authorities state that they currently have 1,161 foreign persons, most of them doctors and nurses
But the auditor general warned that the number may be higher, partly because the boards have problems in identifying employees who have indefinite residence permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures established by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being widely implemented.
This includes passport checks, work permits and skills checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing the policy and guide for the pre-employment of foreigners in the NHS.
The health secretary, Nicola Sturgeon, states: "It was of great interest that this work should be carried out following the terrorist attack at Glasgow airport.
He added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this will be reflected in the update of the pre-employment control guides for all working groups - including foreigners - what they planned to publish next month.
