Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not adequate for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlwinds at the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers were suspected that there could be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays are silent at a height of 54 kilometres from one cloud and behind another, tells Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific magazine "Nature."
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms may have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus this is not the case: if one day there was life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution, "explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface there are temperatures of 500 ° C, oscillating so that temperatures can be reached under zero.
"Possibly, Venus is a" diabolical "twin of the Earth, but it remains a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so much like the Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus's research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of "Nature," according to the researchers' opinion, highlight not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighbouring planets have more common characteristics with the Earth than we had assumed," ESA reports.
Despite the already known storm winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon recalls the wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometres it is almost as large.
This planet also called the dawn star or evening star orbit around the Sun almost 225 days.
But its period of rotation is slower: one day on Venus is 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not look much like the Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On both planets water had been agglomerated that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it was dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, in Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
