It's not the wooden boxes.
Who links the terms Sweden and wooden box, think of Ikea, but don't think of Andy Warhol.
Is that right?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the ninety-four "type" Glow-Box on this list are false.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968 by Andy Warhol, the Modern Museum of Stockholm carried out internal investigations and reached disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes," which the former director of the Pontus Hultén Museum gave to the Modern Museum, are false, and almost a cent of the other "Stockholm" type, "which are in circulation in the international art market, also result.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York City, painted the wooden boxes in red, blue and white, with the same sample that had "Brillo" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, at the 1968 exhibition of his works at the Modern Museum, hundreds of Brillo-cardboard boxes were exposed. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expenses), but were brought directly from the "Brillo" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but examples (which were only objects) exposed.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol made it possible to produce in Sweden glow-boxes of wood, but they were not exposed at the Modern Museum.
Witnesses from those times now speak of the fact that almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auction as originals of the "Brillo-Boxes" of "Stockholm type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
In auctions some of them were bought for over $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in fact, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At this time Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Byström, the head of the conservatives of the Modern Museum, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. First they were printed and embellished their tight plates and then they were painted to oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the copies of the year 1990 shows that the painting was applied with a roller without directly printing the pressed plates. Moreover, it is not about oil paint, but rather about acrylic painting.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from the official list of Brillo-Boxes by Andy Warhol," says Lars Nittve, the director of the Modern Museum Museum and adds that if the Authentication Commission "Andy Warhol Art" in New York will not come to any conclusion, the Modern Museum will classify these six boxes as the copies / objects of exhibition. "
Already in July the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these "serious accusations" in which they are soap dust boxes.
But from that moment on, everything remained in absolute silence.
