In the Philippines, rebel soldiers who had stalled in a hotel in Manila and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have surrendered.
The head Antonio Trillanes, who reproaches the president, corruption and electoral fraud, told a reporter that she could not respond for spilling blood.
The government's loyal soldiers had raided the hotel using tear gas.
Almost two hundred soldiers had been in the building for a few hours.
Almost half of them, including Trillanes, had on Thursday trial for having tried a coup in 2003 that ended in a failure.
He took advantage of the negotiations, suddenly to be able to deposit with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police who were to watch him had obviously moved to their ranks and followed their mutiny.
They entered the "Peninsula" hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government troops blocked the neighborhood around the Noble Hotel.
The president called an urgent session of the Security Cabinet.
Norberto Gonzales, the National Security Adviser, condemned the behaviour of the soldiers.
"People are sick," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to move into our ranks."
General Danilo Lim, who used to run the elite Scout Reangers troop, said that the other military troops wanted to follow the march soon.
The great government critics called for a big demonstration against the president on Thursday.
For months, his government has been reprimanded for corruption.
In 2003 the financial district in Manila was a site that attracted all the attention for the riot that was tried against Arroyo.
The uprising failed after about 24 hours because the army wanted to participate.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven attempts at coup d'état against the democratically elected government in the Philippines.
